import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load a world map shapefile
world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres'))

# Assuming your data is in a DataFrame called 'df' with columns 'matched_country', 'R_Height_cms', and 'B_Height_cms'
# Merge your data with the geographic data
merged_data = world.merge(df[['matched_country', 'R_Height_cms', 'B_Height_cms']], how='left', left_on='name', right_on='matched_country')

The Choropleth Map for R_Height_cms illustrates height distributions across various countries. Darker shades signify taller average heights, with regions like Northern Europe and parts of Africa and Asia showing higher values.¶

The Choropleth Map for B_Height_cms is the same, with regions like Africa and Asia showing higher values.¶

These choropleth maps provide valuable insights into the global distribution of heights among UFC fighters.¶

Analyzing the geographical differences in fighter heights can influence competition results, training methods, and talent identification.¶
